<p>Segment logic frozen 1 week before — assign a named owner and add to collision calendar if the checklist item touches offers across capture, email, SMS, or loyalty.</p>
<p>SMS frequency cap 72h — assign a named owner and add to collision calendar if the checklist item touches offers across capture, email, SMS, or loyalty.</p>
<p>Privy popup pause rules documented — assign a named owner and add to collision calendar if the checklist item touches offers across capture, email, SMS, or loyalty.</p>
<p>Deliverability auth verified — assign a named owner and add to collision calendar if the checklist item touches offers across capture, email, SMS, or loyalty.</p>
<p>Daily unsubscribe monitoring — assign a named owner and add to collision calendar if the checklist item touches offers across capture, email, SMS, or loyalty.</p>
<p>Post-BFCM deliverability audit scheduled — assign a named owner and add to collision calendar if the checklist item touches offers across capture, email, SMS, or loyalty.</p>
<p>Margin after discount tracked daily — assign a named owner and add to collision calendar if the checklist item touches offers across capture, email, SMS, or loyalty.</p>
<h2>FAQ deep dives</h2>
<p><strong>How many BFCM emails?</strong> Calendar-driven waves — not daily blasts 14 days. Quality segments over volume. Stack operators should document this answer in internal runbooks — not rely on tribal knowledge when agencies turn over.</p>
<p><strong>VIP early access required?</strong> Yes for margin — loyalists first, not deepest discount to everyone. Stack operators should document this answer in internal runbooks — not rely on tribal knowledge when agencies turn over.</p>
<p><strong>Sunset before BFCM?</strong> 30–90 day unengaged sunset 4–6 weeks before peak. Stack operators should document this answer in internal runbooks — not rely on tribal knowledge when agencies turn over.</p>
<p><strong>Pause winback?</strong> Yes peak week — conflicting offers and list fatigue. Stack operators should document this answer in internal runbooks — not rely on tribal knowledge when agencies turn over.</p>
<p><strong>SMS BFCM rules?</strong> 72h cap, quiet hours, no email+SMS same discount hour. Stack operators should document this answer in internal runbooks — not rely on tribal knowledge when agencies turn over.</p>
<p><strong>Recent purchaser exclusion?</strong> 7–14 days full-price buyers excluded from sitewide. Stack operators should document this answer in internal runbooks — not rely on tribal knowledge when agencies turn over.</p>
<p><strong>Deliverability prep?</strong> Auth check, avoid cold volume spike, post-peak audit. Stack operators should document this answer in internal runbooks — not rely on tribal knowledge when agencies turn over.</p>
<p><strong>Privy during BFCM?</strong> Pause non-essential capture — focus sends not popups. Stack operators should document this answer in internal runbooks — not rely on tribal knowledge when agencies turn over.</p>
<p><strong>Metrics?</strong> Revenue per send, daily unsub, margin, Jan reactivation. Stack operators should document this answer in internal runbooks — not rely on tribal knowledge when agencies turn over.</p>
<p><strong>Replenishment during BFCM?</strong> Pause or merge into BFCM calendar — no collision. Stack operators should document this answer in internal runbooks — not rely on tribal knowledge when agencies turn over.</p>
<p><strong>When freeze changes?</strong> Segment logic frozen 1 week before; experiments paused 2 weeks. Stack operators should document this answer in internal runbooks — not rely on tribal knowledge when agencies turn over.</p>
<p><strong>Biggest BFCM mistake?</strong> No collision calendar — stack layers independently discount same shoppers daily. Stack operators should document this answer in internal runbooks — not rely on tribal knowledge when agencies turn over.</p>
    </article>
    <div class="space-y-8">
      {toolReviews.map((review) => (
        <ToolReview app={appBySlug(review.slug)!} rank={review.rank} paragraphs={review.paragraphs} />
      ))}
    </div>
    <FaqSection faqs={faqs} title={`FAQ: ${useCaseName}`} />
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
